    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Try to answer this based on these great comments:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><p>One single <code>next()</code> call has a totally different time complexity compared with the whole iterating process.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>TreeMap in Java is based on Red-Black Tree, which is a balanced binary search tree.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Refer to <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/TreeMap.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/TreeMap.html</a></p>\n<ol start=\"3\">\n<li><p>Iterating a whole TreeMap should have the same time complexity as traversing the Red-Black Tree(For pre-order in-order or post-order traveral). So time complexity should be <code>O(n)</code> where <code>n</code> is the key(or value, or key-value mapping) count.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>For a single <code>next</code> call, we can do it in <code>O(1)</code>. If a whole <code>O(n)</code> time complexity is true, this should be trivial.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n"
  } ],
